events.description: Fatimid caliph al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah assassinates the eunuch chief minister Barjawan and assumes control of the government.

events.description: The Great German Pilgrimage is attacked on Good Friday by Beduin bandits, suffering heavy losses.

events.description: The Council of Pisa convenes, in an attempt to heal the Western Schism.
events.html: • 1409 – The Council of Pisa convenes, in an attempt to heal the Western Schism.

events.description: Hernán Cortés, entering province of Tabasco, defeats Tabascan Indians.
events.html: • 1519 – Hernán Cortés, entering province of Tabasco, defeats Tabascan Indians.[7]

events.description: Jerome Savage takes out a sub-lease to start the Newington Butts Theatre outside London.
events.html: • 1576 – Jerome Savage takes out a sub-lease to start the Newington Butts Theatre outside London.

events.description: Sir Walter Raleigh is granted a patent to colonize Virginia.
events.html: • 1584 – Sir Walter Raleigh is granted a patent to colonize Virginia.

events.description: Saturn's largest moon, Titan, is discovered by Christiaan Huygens.
events.html: • 1655 – Saturn's largest moon, Titan, is discovered by Christiaan Huygens.

events.description: A French fleet anchors nears Fife Ness as part of the planned French invasion of Britain.
events.html: • 1708 – A French fleet anchors nears Fife Ness as part of the planned French invasion of Britain.[8]

events.description: Bach's chorale cantata "Wie schön leuchtet der Morgenstern, BWV 1", is first performed on the Feast of the Annunciation, coinciding with Palm Sunday.

events.description: Daskalogiannis leads the people of Sfakia in the first Greek uprising against the Ottoman rule

events.description: The Treaty of Amiens is signed as a "Definitive Treaty of Peace" between France and the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1802 – The Treaty of Amiens is signed as a "Definitive Treaty of Peace" between France and the United Kingdom.

events.description: The Swansea and Mumbles Railway, then known as the Oystermouth Railway, becomes the first passenger-carrying railway in the world.
events.html: • 1807 – The Swansea and Mumbles Railway, then known as the Oystermouth Railway, becomes the first passenger-carrying railway in the world.

events.description: Percy Bysshe Shelley is expelled from the University of Oxford for publishing the pamphlet The Necessity of Atheism.
events.html: • 1811 – Percy Bysshe Shelley is expelled from the University of Oxford for publishing the pamphlet The Necessity of Atheism.

events.description: Greek War of Independence: Traditional date of the start of the Greek War of Independence. The war had actually begun on 23 February 1821 (Julian calendar).
events.html: • 1821 – Greek War of Independence: Traditional date of the start of the Greek War of Independence. The war had actually begun on 23 February 1821 (Julian calendar).

events.description: New Zealand Legislative Council pass the first Militia Act constituting the New Zealand Army.
events.html: • 1845 – New Zealand Legislative Council pass the first Militia Act constituting the New Zealand Army.[11]

events.description: American Civil War: In Virginia during the Siege of Petersburg, Confederate forces temporarily capture Fort Stedman from the Union before being repulsed.
events.html: • 1865 – American Civil War: In Virginia during the Siege of Petersburg, Confederate forces temporarily capture Fort Stedman from the Union before being repulsed.

events.description: Coxey's Army, the first significant American protest march, departs Massillon, Ohio for Washington, D.C.
events.html: • 1894 – Coxey's Army, the first significant American protest march, departs Massillon, Ohio for Washington, D.C.

events.description: The Greek football club P.A.E. G.S. Diagoras is founded in the city of Rhodes.
events.html: • 1905 – The Greek football club P.A.E. G.S. Diagoras is founded in the city of Rhodes.[12]

events.description: In New York City, the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire kills 146 garment workers.
events.html: • 1911 – In New York City, the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire kills 146 garment workers.[13]

events.html: • 1911 – Andrey Yushchinsky is murdered in Kiev, leading to the Beilis affair.
